                        <h5 class="head-font"><strong>What about other tracking technologies, like web beacons?</strong></h5>
                        <p>Cookies are not the only way to recognize or track visitors to a website. Other similar technologies, like web beacons (sometimes called "tracking pixels" or "clear gifs"), may also be used from time to time. These are tiny graphic files that contain a unique identifier that enables recognition when someone has visited the website or opened an email containing them. This allows for the monitoring of traffic patterns, delivery or communication of cookies, understanding whether users have come from third-party websites, improving site performance, and measuring the success of email marketing campaigns. In many instances, these technologies are reliant on cookies to function properly, and declining cookies may impair their functioning.</p>
                        <h5 class="head-font"><strong>Do you use Flash cookies?</strong></h5>
                        <p>Websites may also use "Flash Cookies" (also known as Local Shared Objects or "LSOs") for site operations, fraud prevention, and other purposes. Users can adjust their Flash player settings to block Flash Cookies storage using the tools contained in the Website Storage Settings Panel, or by going to the Global Storage Settings Panel and following the instructions. However, note that setting the Flash Player to restrict or limit acceptance of Flash Cookies may reduce or impede the functionality of some Flash applications.</p>
                        <h5 class="head-font"><strong>Do you serve targeted advertising?</strong></h5>
                        <p>Third parties may serve cookies on users' computers or mobile devices to serve advertising through the website. These companies may use information about visits to this and other websites to provide relevant advertisements about goods and services that may be of interest. They may also use technology to measure the effectiveness of advertisements, using cookies or web beacons to collect information. The information collected through this process does not identify users' name, contact details, or other direct identification unless provided by users.</p>
